<div class="markdown"><h1>Linear model fitting</h1><p>This is an example tutorial showing how to fit a linear model with <a href="https://juliastats.org/GLM.jl">GLM.jl</a> and plot it with <a href="https://makie.juliaplots.org/stable/">Makie.jl</a>.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Let's start by generating the linear relationship</p><p class="tex">$$y = 2x + \epsilon,$$</p><p>where <span class="tex">$\epsilon$</span> is random noise.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>using DataFrames</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>df = let
    X = 1:100
    Y = [2x + rand(1:20) for x in X]
    DataFrame(; X, Y)
end</code></pre>
<table><tbody><tr><th></th><th>X</th><th>Y</th></tr><tr><td>1</td><td>1</td><td>17</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>2</td><td>11</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>3</td><td>11</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>4</td><td>21</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>5</td><td>21</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>6</td><td>17</td></tr><tr><td>7</td><td>7</td><td>34</td></tr><tr><td>8</td><td>8</td><td>24</td></tr><tr><td>9</td><td>9</td><td>24</td></tr><tr><td>10</td><td>10</td><td>36</td></tr><tr><td>...</td></tr><tr><td>100</td><td>100</td><td>211</td></tr></tbody></table>


<div class="markdown"><p>In a plot, the data looks as follows:</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>using CairoMakie</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>lines(df.X, df.Y)</code></pre>
<img src="data:image/png;base64,"/>


<div class="markdown"><p>On this data, a linear model can be fitted:</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>using GLM</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>model = lm(@formula(Y ~ X), df);</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>Which gives estimates for the intercept and slope:</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>intercept, slope = GLM.coef(model)</code></pre>
<pre class="code-output documenter-example-output" id="var-intercept">2-element Vector{Float64}:
 10.376363636363783
  1.9994779477947766</pre>


<div class="markdown"><p>With this, we can determine all values which are "predicted" by the fitted model:</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>Y_fitted = [intercept + slope * x for x in df.X];</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>And plot it again:</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>let
    fig = Figure()
    ax = Axis(fig[1, 1])

    lines!(ax, df.X, df.Y, label="true")
    lines!(ax, df.X, Y_fitted; color=:black, linestyle=:dash, label="fitted")

    axislegend(ax; position=:lt)
    fig
end</code></pre>
